node.text:
We literally could not be more excited to finally release this video and share how amazing @_lillianbradley is 🥰 Cuddle up, watch this nursery come to life, tell us what you think, then NOMINATE a friend for our next nursery makeover (link in bio!!) 🥳

We couldn’t have done this without the help of our interior designer, @emilytaylordesigns, and so many amazing companies that donated their products to this project!
Wallpaper: @loomwell
1960s vintage rug: @vintagethreadsco
Throw + leather pouf: @woven.nook
Glider: @furnishh_
Bookshelves: @woodyoubuy
Crib sheet: @thebabycubby @copperpearl
Crib pillow: @ebbandthread
@plumandsparrow supplied all the baskets, the Moses basket, bassinet stand, changing basket, macrame wall hanging, and macrame chandelier!
📽 Videographer: @kaitcfilms
#sparrowmamanurserymakeover

node.text:
“This is the moment I looked in the mirror for the first time. Legs still tingling from the epidural, I stood in front of the mirror and looked at my squishy belly. I was alone. For the first time in over nine months. It was just me. 

This moment was the first of a few hard moments in my transition into the 4th trimester. I wasn’t delusional going into surrogacy. I had read many blogs and testimonies from other surrogates about their experience. But none of those stories prepared me for those first few days postpartum… 

Nothing can prepare you for walking out of the maternity ward/hospital after giving birth without a newborn snuggled in their car seat. 

Nothing can prepare you for getting home from the hospital and cutting off your hospital wrist bands. Each cut with the scissors felt like I was severing myself from the journey. For months I had such an important role and duty, and this signified the ‘end.’ Nothing can prepare you for the crash of hormones. All of day 3, I was a mess of emotions and bloodshot eyes. 

Nothing can prepare you for hearing a baby cry in Target and losing every bit of strength you have not to cry in public. I’m sure I looked like a crazy person as I wandered the Hearth & Hand section with tears streaming down my cheeks. 

These moments were hard and I’ll never forget this transition into the #4thtrimester of this #surrogacyjourney 🕊

There is still beauty in these moments because they made me stronger. And I’ll always know my moments of suffering could never hold a light to the twelve years my intended parents waited for Baby F.”
- words and photo from @ohheymamamack
#truthtalktuesday

node.text:
Last week was world breastfeeding week and we loved sitting back and seeing all of your beautiful posts + words 💕 We just had to share @seasonsofpeaches’s post that taught us so much! 

“BOTH are BEAUTIFUL
BOTH can be used to bond
BOTH are hard
BOTH are tiring
BOTH are physically demanding 
BOTH are time consuming
BOTH can give your baby what they need
BOTH we will be judged for, so we might as well just do what is best for us and our family

Breastfeeding is difficult for so many people, in so many different ways. For World Breastfeeding Week I want to show my support to the people who were unable to breastfeed. This is often a loss we need to grieve. It can also bring on feelings of guilt and inadequacy. No one deserves to feel this way 🤍

Some of the reasons a person may not be able to breastfeed include:

🍼Mental Health struggles
🍼Mastectomy
🍼Being Trans
🍼Birth Trauma
🍼Being a victim of sexual abuse
🍼Low supply
🍼Latch issues with baby for various reasons
🍼Lack of support resources
🍼Needing to return to work early 
🍼Baby being in the NICU for an extended period of time 
🍼Illness within the mother and/or chemotherapy 

Enough with the ‘Breast is Best’ mentality. It’s not helpful, it’s hurtful. We are enough for our babies, no matter how we feed them 🤍 

*I know breastfeeding can be a choice and the choice not to breastfeed, because you simply don’t want to, is 100% valid. You don’t need a reason 🤍 Today I just decided to focus on those who didn’t have a choice.”

node.text:
“I took this picture yesterday morning. After a hard night the night before and in the middle of a rough morning. I was at my breaking point, crying while feeding and texting Chase saying, “I can’t do this.” Because at the time I didn’t want to.

I looked back at this picture after taking it, though, and saw “Mama” written on my shirt. And the chain of my necklace tucked beneath my Mama shirt that says “Eli” on the pendant. And I remembered that I not only CAN do it, but that I AM doing it. And WILL continue to do it.

And that’s right there is what makes motherhood powerful. The ability to rally. The second, third, and fourth wind that we always muster up. That, right when we want to quit, we simply don’t.

The emptiness, tests, losses, and changes all make up a strong, relentless, and powerful new identity: Mama.”

Thank you for these beautiful works, @fittestcore 🤍 and for reminding us that we CAN do it, and we ARE doing it!
#truthtalktuesday
